            "id": "35fd3ec298834102a08b2",
            "questionText": "A robotic arm in a manufacturing plant picks up an object. The arm moves in three stages. First, it moves horizontally a distance of $!$0.5\\,\\text{m}$!$ in $!$1\\,\\text{s}$!$ with uniform acceleration. Second, it holds the object stationary for $!$2\\,\\text{s}$!$. Third, it moves vertically upwards $!$0.2\\,\\text{m}$!$ in $!$0.5\\,\\text{s}$!$ with uniform acceleration. Considering both horizontal and vertical movements, calculate the average velocity of the robotic arm during the entire motion.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "80161fae2afa4c70b3389",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the net displacement of the arm. In the horizontal stage, it moves a certain distance and in the vertical stage, it moves upward. Which formula best represents how you calculate the displacement (as a vector difference between the final and initial positions)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "42f9486d-bb12-41c1-a177-31ddbff30efd"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta s = s_{final} - s_{initial}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$s = s_0 + vt$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{\\Delta s}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "2a897a453b744a22b69d3",
                    "stepText": "Great, now add the durations of all three stages (the horizontal movement, the stationary period, and the vertical movement) to calculate the total time of the motion.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "a834792cb4e34da784d15",
                    "stepText": "Next, compute the average velocity vector components by dividing each displacement component by the total time. Which formula correctly relates displacement, time, and average velocity?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "c1170020-784b-45f6-9ec5-8dfe77a1f9d0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{\\Delta s}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\Delta s \\times \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\Delta s - \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ead004413f344e0bb4aed",
                    "stepText": "Finally, calculate the magnitude of the average velocity vector using the vector components. Which mathematical operation should be used to obtain the magnitude from its components?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.154"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$|v| = \\sqrt{v_x^2+v_y^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$|v| = v_x+v_y$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$|v| = \\frac{v_x+v_y}{2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
